<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-101-126  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 101 126.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 13 1989 v23 n11 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cray machines cited in Japan scandal. (Cray Research Inc., RecruitCosmos Co.'s Hisashi Shinto)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Valigra, Lori.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Cray Research Inc's supercomputers surfaced during the RecruitCosmos Inc influence peddling scandal in Tokyo in Mar 1989.andO;Although Cray itself was not implicated, alleged kickbacks fromthe resale of Cray systems resulted in the arrest of the formerchairman of Nippon Telegraph andamp; Telephone Corp, Hisashi Shinto, whoresigned in late 1989 amid allegations he illegally receivedapproximately $70,000.andP;  Shinto's arrest places his company at theheart of the scandal and more strongly implies misdeeds by toppoliticians, including former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone.andO;Japanese television reports that proceeds from Recruit Cosmos Costock were actually kickbacks to Shinto for the purchase of twoCray supercomputers.andP;  The Crays form the 'legs' of a triangularrelationship among Shinto, Nakasone and the former chairman ofRecruit Co, the parent firm of Recruit Cosmos.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Cray Research Inc. (products)Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (officials and employees)Recruit Cosmos Co. (investigations).andO;Ticker:    CYR; D.NOJ.andO;Topic:     SupercomputersCourt CasesJapanPoliticsExecutiveLegal Issues.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Hisashi Shinto. (portrait)Person:    Shinto, Hisashi (arrest of).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>